{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RkRijrNuw2GZfdmXXW2XG8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019vH8XCP7sXjfVM67Tg3uJD","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-8-2-expand-state-types-for-rust && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The src/ directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading README.md in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file story.md contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here is its content:\n\n---\n# Story 8-2: Expand State Types for Rust\n\n## Status: verifying\n\n## Story\n\nAs a developer,\nI want the harness state to support Rust-specific fields,\nSo that coverage tool and OTLP config are correctly stored without type errors.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [x] AC1: Given a Rust project is initialized, when state is written, then coverage.tool accepts cargo-tarpaulin without type errors <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n- [x] AC2: Given a Rust project has OTLP configured, when state is written, then otlp.rust_env_hint field is present with value OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n---\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via docker exec codeharness-verify ...\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: codeharness-verify\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: docker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n- Example: docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n- Example: docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness init --json\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- codeharness — the project CLI\n- curl, jq — for querying observability endpoints\n- node, npm — Node.js runtime\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]\n- Capture exit codes: docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo EXIT:\\$?'\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- VictoriaLogs (logs): http://localhost:9428\n  - Example: curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\n- VictoriaMetrics (metrics): http://localhost:8428\n  - Example: curl 'http://localhost:8428/api/v1/query?query=up'\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH docker exec command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n  [OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: verification/8-2-expand-state-types-for-rust-proof.md\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n## AC N: <description>\n\n**Verdict: PASS/FAIL**\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n\\`\\`\\`output\n<actual output>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nIMPORTANT: Only use bash and output as code fence languages. Never use bare code fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. ALL commands MUST use docker exec codeharness-verify ... — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. Do NOT attempt to access source code — there is no src/ directory in this workspace.\n3. Report REAL failures — if a feature does not work, report that as a verification failure. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. Every AC needs functional evidence — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.\n6. [ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n7. Never switch to unit-testable verification. If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\" 2>&1","description":"Run black-box verifier session","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":547,"cache_read_input_tokens":55643,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":547},"output_tokens":58,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d94a92ae-93cf-430a-a395-7caa50486212","uuid":"51fabaf3-b689-4c2a-8a95-3776d4ab3b2d"}
